1. d4 {1.d4 opens the center and grabs space. It is the foundation of the Jobava London, where White quickly adds Nc3 and Bf4 for natural development and pressure, without heavy theory. Engine evaluation after the move: +0.18 (roughly equal).}
1... d5 {Takes the classical center and establishes a presence on d5/e4. White continues the Jobava plan: Nc3, Bf4 and pressure. Engine evaluation after the move: +0.77 (a slight edge for White).}
( 1... e5 {An attempt to break in the center. Usually after dxe5 lines and files open in favor of White's developed pieces. Engine evaluation after the move: +1.27 (a clear edge for White).} 2. dxe5 {Opens the center and exploits ...e5. After the exchanges the f4-bishop and b5-knight are very active, and Black often runs into tactical trouble around c7 and d5. Engine evaluation after the move: +0.75 (a slight edge for White).}
2... Nc6 {Active development, but it weakens the defense of c7 and invites Nb5 with threats of Nxc7+ and Nd6 — exactly the structure White welcomes. Engine evaluation after the move: +1.16 (a clear edge for White).}
( 2... Bc5 {In the 1...e5 gambit line, develops with tempo against f2. White develops with Nf3 and Nc3 and keeps the extra pawn. Engine evaluation after the move: +1.70 (a clear edge for White).} 3. Nf3 {Natural development supporting d4 and e5, preparing short castling and completing White's solid setup. Engine evaluation after the move: +1.08 (a clear edge for White).}
3... d6 {A restrained move preparing ...e5 or a hypermodern setup. White grabs the center with e4 and plays on space. Engine evaluation after the move: +1.86 (a clear edge for White).}
4. exd6 {The pawn recaptures and keeps the extra material from the gambit, while opening lines that favor White's development. Engine evaluation after the move: +1.09 (a clear edge for White).}
4... Ne7 {A knight heading to g6 to pressure e5. White completes development and keeps the material edge. Engine evaluation after the move: +2.04 (a large edge for White).}
5. Nc3 {The signature move of the Jobava London: the knight develops to c3, pressuring d5 and e4 without blocking the c-pawn. This keeps the Nb5 jump and fast pressure available, unlike the classical London with c3. Engine evaluation after the move: +1.16 (a clear edge for White).} )
