( 1... f5 {An aggressive Dutch-like setup, but it weakens the king. White develops with Nc3 and pressures the weaknesses. Engine evaluation after the move: +1.04 (a clear edge for White).} 2. Nc3 {The signature move of the Jobava London: the knight develops to c3, pressuring d5 and e4 without blocking the c-pawn. This keeps the Nb5 jump and fast pressure available, unlike the classical London with c3. Engine evaluation after the move: +0.47 (a slight edge for White).} )
( 1... Na6 {An offbeat development to the rim. White grabs the center (e4) and develops comfortably with an edge. Engine evaluation after the move: +1.55 (a clear edge for White). An inaccuracy that plays into White's hands.} 2. Nc3 {The signature move of the Jobava London: the knight develops to c3, pressuring d5 and e4 without blocking the c-pawn. This keeps the Nb5 jump and fast pressure available, unlike the classical London with c3. Engine evaluation after the move: +0.62 (a slight edge for White).}
2... d6 {A restrained move preparing ...e5 or a hypermodern setup. White grabs the center with e4 and plays on space. Engine evaluation after the move: +1.49 (a clear edge for White).}
3. e4 {Grabs the full center. Against a hypermodern setup (...g6/...d6) White builds a big center and prepares e5 to seize the initiative. Engine evaluation after the move: +1.06 (a clear edge for White).}
